<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="67" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,310,1377,1403]" box="[189,310,1377,1403]" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1377,1403]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="3" pageNumber="67" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1377,1403]" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[188,1399,1423,1555]" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">
Forewing dark brown with indistinct transverse white stripes (
<figureCitation box="[908,1030,1423,1450]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1920,1946]" captionTargetBox="[216,1370,265,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-12@4.[216,1370,265,1881]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. Machaerotypus stigmosus Li &amp; Chen sp. nov. A, C, E. Paratype, ♀ (IEGU), habitus in dorsal, frontal and lateral view. B, D, F. Paratype, ♂ (IEGU), habitus in dorsal, frontal and lateral view. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6761663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6761663/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Figs 1E–F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1041,1114,1424,1450]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[189,232,1952,1978]" captionTargetBox="[218,1363,278,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-14@5.[205,1382,265,1913]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 2. Machaerotypus stigmosus Li &amp; Chen sp. nov. A. Paratype, ♂ (IEGU), forewing. B. Paratype, ♀ (IEGU), forewing. C. Paratype, ♀ (IEGU), hind wing. Scale bars: A–C = 0.5 mm. a–e = white parts." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6761667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6761667/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">2A–B</figureCitation>
), half of anterior surface and margin densely clothed with coarse denticulation; aedeagal shaft with tiny dorsal hump at base (
<figureCitation box="[198,290,1494,1520]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[189,232,1922,1948]" captionTargetBox="[216,1365,268,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-11@6.[216,1371,265,1883]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 3. Machaerotypus stigmosus Li &amp; Chen sp. nov., paratype, ♂ (IEGU). A, C, D. Genitalia in lateral, posterior and ventral view. B, E. Aedeagus, posterior and lateral view. F. Style, dorsal view. G. Lateral plate. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6761669" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6761669/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
), dorsal margin dentate in distal half; second valvulae with broad dorsal hump on basal half (
<figureCitation box="[200,292,1529,1555]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1920,1946]" captionTargetBox="[194,1395,633,1809]" captionTargetId="figure-104@7.[189,1398,621,1881]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 4. Machaerotypus stigmosus Li &amp; Chen sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (IEGU). A–B. Genitalia in lateral and ventral view. C. Sternite VII, ventral view. D. First valvulae, lateral view. E. Second valvulae, lateral view. F. Third valvulae (gonoplac), lateral view. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6761671" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6761671/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="67" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,324,1595,1621]" box="[189,324,1595,1621]" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1595,1621]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="3" pageNumber="67" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1595,1621]" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1399,1641,1703]" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">
The word ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Li &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2022" box="[320,436,1642,1667]" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Machaerotypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stigmosus">
<emphasis box="[320,436,1642,1667]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="67">stigmosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ is a Latinized adjective derived from the Greek word ‘stigma’ (spot), referring to the forewing with many spots.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
